Measurement of $CP$ violation that varies with decay time in $B^0$ decays into $J/\psi K^0_\mathrm{S}$ and $B^0$ decays into $\psi(2S) K^0_\mathrm{S}$ is reported. The $J/\psi$ is identified through two electrons, and the $\psi(2S)$ is identified through two muons. The analysis is based on data from $pp$ collisions collected by the LHCb experiment at 7 and 8 TeV, with an integrated luminosity of 3 $\mathrm{fb}^{-1}$. The $CP$-violation parameters are found to be \begin{equation*} \begin{aligned}
C\left(B^0\rightarrow J/\psi K^0_\mathrm{S}\right)&=\phantom{+}\,0.12\,\pm\,0.07\pm\,0.02\,,\\
S\left(B^0\rightarrow J/\psi K^0_\mathrm{S}\right)&=\phantom{+}\,0.83\,\pm\,0.08\pm\,0.01\,,\\
C\left(B^0\rightarrow\psi(2S) K^0_\mathrm{S}\right)&=-\,0.05\,\pm\,0.10\pm\,0.01\,,\\
S\left(B^0\rightarrow\psi(2S) K^0_\mathrm{S}\right)&=\phantom{+}\,0.84\,\pm\,0.10\pm\,0.01\,,
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*} where $C$ represents $CP$ violation in the direct decay, and $S$ indicates $CP$ violation in the interference between the direct decay amplitudes and those after $B^0$-$\overline{B}^0$ oscillation. The uncertainties are divided into statistical and systematic components. These findings align with a prior LHCb study involving $B^0\rightarrow J/\psi K^0_\mathrm{S}$ decays where the $J/\psi$ was identified using two muons. The combined averages of all three LHCb results are \begin{equation*} \begin{aligned}
C\left(B^0\rightarrow[c\bar{c}]K^0_\mathrm{S}\right)&=-0.017 \pm 0.029\,,\\
S\left(B^0\rightarrow[c\bar{c}]K^0_\mathrm{S}\right)&=\phantom{+}0.760 \pm 0.034\,,
\end{aligned} \end{equation*} assuming negligible higher-order contributions to the decay amplitudes. The uncertainties encompass statistical and systematic effects.
